Instead of the vague and unscientific division of people into the middle, lower and upper classes, social class can be understood as a material and relational concept. At the core, class is about the division of society into a minority of people that own and control the means of production and the majority of property-less masses, that must toil in some way or another for the owning class. We are talking not about the arbitrary division of society into "upper", "middle", or "lower" classes, but into exploiter and exploited classes; slaves and masters, lords and serfs, and today, capitalists and workers. The essence of class, therefore, is about exploitation, as the owning class lives well and prospers based on surplus labour done by the working classes.

