In a capitalist society, the ruling class are those who monopolize the means of producing goods and services - firms, factories, technology, buildings, even land itself - also known as capitalists. While mostly a topic for another day, the capitalist class has long exercised state power and violence, directly and indirectly, to enforce their exclusive ownership over society's vital resources. The working class can therefore own no such capital and must sell their labour power for a wage to the ruling class to survive. Somewhere in between the two classes exists a small layer of those that live both on exploitation and their labour, which some might call the “middle class”, for example, small business owners, self-employed professionals, and managers. While there is a lot more room for nuance in this type of analysis, especially on differences within classes, this is the essential class structure of capitalism.

